article.description:
Rookie Temeka Johnson scored four points in the
final 94 seconds, and DeLisha Milton-Jones added 15 points to lead the Washington Mystics past the Seattle Storm 78-71 on Wednesday.
article.headline: Rookie Johnson clutch in waning seconds
article.linkText: Milton-Jones leads Mystics to sixth win in eight games
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- At just 5-foot-3, Washington's Temeka Johnson can
add a pull-up jumper over Sue Bird to the list of tough shots she's
hit in her rookie season.

Leading by two, Johnson made the jumper over the 5-9 Bird with
37.3 seconds left to lift the Mystics past the Seattle Storm 78-71
on Wednesday.

Johnson, who finished with 12 points, scored four in the final
94 seconds to give the Mystics (9-8) their sixth win in eight
games.

"Usually Temeka is able to go by you. But her pull-up jump shot
... it's amazing how she can get it off on bigger people,"
Washington coach Richie Adubato said. "She's done that to people
6-foot, 6-1."

While Johnson was key in the final minutes, DeLisha Milton-Jones
carried Washington for most of the second half.

Scoreless at halftime, Milton-Jones made all four 3-point
attempts in the second half, finishing with 15 points. The four
3-pointers was a career-high for the seven-year veteran.

"The opportunities were there and my teammates found me in the
corner," said Milton-Jones. "Sometimes you just throw it up there
and they go in."

Alana Beard also added 15 points for the Mystics, who improved
to 4-3 on the road. Charlotte Smith-Taylor had 11.

The defending champion Storm (8-10) have lost six of their last
seven, and fell to 5-3 at home.

Iziane Castro Marques led Seattle with 19 points. Lauren Jackson
added 17, but was held to just five in the second half. Bird
finished with 16 points after going 0-for-6 in the first half.

"Right now, we're killing ourselves," Jackson said. "It's
frustrating to be out there ... because I don't know what it's
going to take."

Tied at 69 with 2:30 remaining, Washington's Chasity Melvin
scored in the paint before Bird turned the ball over after she said
she was poked in the eye. That led to an uncontested layup by
Johnson.

Castro Marques made an 18-footer to pull to 73-71, but Johnson
milked the clock and hit the jumper over Bird. The Mystics hit
three free throws in the final seconds to seal the game.

"I had to take what the defense gave me," Johnson said. "They
were playing me more for the drive, so the jumper was available."

Washington shot 64 percent in the first half and finished at 58
percent. The Mystics outrebounded the Storm 27-20.

"Defensively, we're talking about the same things here,
unfortunately," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said. "We've got to
get a little bit more aggressive defensively and figure out how we
can, one through five, play better."

Bird threatened to take over the game, scoring 10 points in the
opening 4:12 of the second half, including a 3-pointer that capped
a 13-2 Seattle run for a 51-46 lead.

Beard and Milton-Jones kept the Mystics close, combining to
score Washington's first 18 second-half points. Milton-Jones'
3-pointer with 9:36 left gave the Mystics a 59-58 lead.

The teams traded baskets and were tied at 66 when Milton-Jones
made her fourth 3-pointer, giving Washington a 69-66 lead with 3:54
left.

It was the first game of a five-game West Coast swing for the
Mystics.

"You really have to try and get the first one when you have
energy and when you have your legs under you," Adubato said.

The Mystics swept the season series with the Storm. They beat
Seattle 64-52 on June 10, when the Storm played without Bird, who
was out with a broken nose.
